#Typing HELP with no arguments will give you a list of things you can get
help on.

#
AUCTION
Auctions on crimson mud 2 are for selling and buying of equipment.
Please use this for those purposes only.  
&BAuction is not a means of identification of objects.  For that
you need to buy scrolls or use the spell of identify.&n  

&RCaution: Anyone can buy anything from an auction.  If you put
something up for auction or a mob does it.  Do not cry to the
immortal staff about this.  This is part of the game.&n

See Also: BID

#
IMMORTAL_ABUSE

Immortal abuse will result in review of immortal status, and could result 
in the loss of immortal standing, login ability (ie, siteban), or the 
removal of players (if situation involves use of immortal for mortal multi
benefit).

Immortal abuse can include, but is NOT limited to, the following:

Casting spells (locate has NO excuse being used by immortals without some
form of announcement beforehand - There may be instances where using locate
may be useful or productive in problem solving or handling mortal affairs.
However, immortals have more useful tools in handling these scenarios) can
result in abuse consideration.

Transferring / summoning players without permission in UNNECESSARY 
situations.  If a legitmate purpose is being served (immortal intervention
for arguments, dealing with rules infractions, being asked for a transfer 
to talk, etc.), there is no area for abuse.  Transferring people to 
unwanted locations, or transferring in a manner creating a nuisance are 
situations where abuse can be claimed.

Loading equipment for personal mortal / avatar use.  Loading gear for 
serious playing nature for personal players of ANY level is abuse.  Novelty
equipment, such as eq with no stats (or negligible stats), is not abuse.  
Any eq that may aid game play OR influence the playing environment (eq 
loaded to sell / trade would be an example) should not be loaded for 
personal use.

When in doubt, ASK.  If it seems wrong, don't do it.  If it's questionable,
don't do it til you can consult with a &Y*BOSS*&n.

#
ADJUST

syntax: adjust <spell #> <Character Name> <New Duration>

This commands allows an immortal to adjust the duration of a spell that is
currently affecting a character.  There is a limit to the number of ticks 
you can adjust the spells up to, but keep in mind that some spells should
never be set to that limit. (In fact most shouldn't.) Use common sense and
good judgement when adjust spell durations, and please do not abuse the 
command.  If it is found that this command is being abused more 
restrictions may have to be implemented.

See also "IMM_RULES" "IMM_RULES2" "IMMORTAL_ABUSE"  

#
DISABLE

syntax:  disable <command>
         disable spell <spell #>

This command will disable a command or spell.  It requires the mud to be
rebooted in order to be effective.

Note:  This is a ADMIN command.

#
BOUNTY

 PK players may place bounties on other PK players at the Bounty Master located
west of the Questmaster.  The minimum bounty is 100 million coins, with the 
maximum set to 1 billion coins. 

SYNTAX: bounty <name> <amount>

 Also note that the Bounty Master will take his cut of 25%, so when you place a
bounty of 100 million coins on someones head, you'll actually pay 125 million
coins (100 million + 25%). If you try to place a bounty on someone who already
has a bounty, the money you pay is added to his/her current bounty total, up to
the maximum of 1 billion coins. 

 When you kill a player with a bounty on his/her head, the head falls from the
victims body and drops into your inventory. When this occurs, there is a 50% 
chance that the victims head equipment will come with it. The equipment becomes
property of the killing player, and can be removed from the head via the normal
means of collecting items from corpses. However, should the killing player fail
to remove the equipment prior to returning the head to the Bounty Master, the
equipment will be auctioned and is fair game for anyone to bid on.

 To collect the bounty on someone you killed, simply drop the head at the  
Bounty Master.

 If you find a bounty on your head, you may remove it at a 25% markup:

SYNTAX: bounty payoff

To see a list of bounties, from anywhere, use bounty list:

SYNTAX: bounty list

*IMPORTANT* -- Only PK players may place and collect bounties. The only 
            exception to this is when a mob places a bounty on a players
            head. When this happens, anyone, PK or not may collect the 
            bounty as per the methods above. 

            *NOTE* Only players above level 34 can have bounties placed on
                   them by mobs, and when this occurs, there is no chance
                   of losing headgear.

#
PKSTEALING

Stealing from other players in PK is not allowed.  Do not do it.  That 
is all.

#
SLOTS

Generally different races have a different number of equipment slots that 
they can fill.  Generally speaking, of course they are as follows:

Non-tailed humanoid characters:  18 Equipment Slots
Characters with tails:  16 Equipment Slots (No FEET, LEGS, or WAIST slots)
Thri-kreen:             17 Equipment Slots (No FEET or HEAD slots)
Centaur:                17 Equipment Slots (No FEET or WAIST slots)

The available equipment slots are noted below:

LIGHT-SOURCE - held as a light source.
FINGER - worn on finger, you can wear 2 of these.
NECK - worn around neck, you can wear 2 of these.
BODY - worn on mid-body.
HEAD - worn on the head.
LEGS - worn on the legs.
FEET - worn on the feet.
HANDS - worn on the hands.
ARMS - worn on the arms.
SHIELD - worn as a shield.
ABOUT - worn about the body.
WAIST - worn around the waist.
WRIST - worn about the wrist, you can wear 2 of these.
WIELD - object is wielded.
HOLD - held in the hand.
TAIL - Worn on the lower body of Yuan-ti.
4LEGS - Worn on the legs of Thri-Keen and Centaur, 2 of these can be worn.


#
IQR

IQR - Imm Quest Rules (Avatar Quests)

Quest Rules:
1) Must have 5 avatars, 3 of which are in different clans (prevents
   favoritism)
2) Items used must be 3% or higher, and not max.  Some times, with proper 
   approval, the 3% can be removed, and 2% or a 1% can be allowed.  (See 
   a &P*GOD*&n)
3) No more than 2 pieces of eq should be used in a quest, per participant.
   Thus, if you have 5 participants, do not use more than 10 pieces.   
4) If a no_rent item is already loaded in the game, it can't be loaded anymore, 
   qeq wise (prevents repetitive items).  
5) Immortals who run the quests must pay attention to events happening in their
   quests.  It is not the responsibility of all immortals to take care of quests
   that they did not load.  If you start a quest, finish it.
6) There are some times when the rules can be put to the shelf, but only 
   with proper approval.  Approval may ONLY be obtained from a person with a
   *GOD* flag.

#
WIZTITLE

The text to the left of an immortals name on who.

COMMAND WIZTITLE:

Command to set an immortals wiztitle.

Usage:	wiztitle set <name> <string>	sets the immortals initial wiz-
					title.
	wiztitle add <name> <string>	adds additional wiztitles to the
					immortal
	wiztitle show <name>		shows the immortals wiztitles.
	
	wiztitles remove <name> <index>	removes a wiztitle from an immortal
					<index> is found from wiztitle show. 										    

#
DARKLING

Suggested levels: 20-40.         Align: Varies.

Start off by heading west through the woods next to Midgaard.  Eventually 
you'll turn south, walking in this direction until you hit the foothills of
Haon-Dor forest.  Then turn again towards the west to enter the land of the
darklings.  

#
REIMB_LYING

Lying during a reimbursement is lying, period.  Whether you asked for an 
item, or merely kept the item due to an immortal mistake, you are claiming 
a piece of equipment that is not yours.

Lying during reimbursements is VERY serious.  Lying to immortals is an 
offense, and lying about equipment for your own gain and taking ADVANTAGE 
of immortals who are trying to help you regain your equipment has very dire 
consequences.

Offenses include any matters related to reimbursements.  Asking for 
equipment you did not have, keeping equipment that was erroneously given 
to you, or AIDING people in reimbursement lying / cheating.  NOTE: Aiding 
an offense is just as serious as committing it.  You knowingly and willingly
engaged in deception.

The consequences are as follows:

1st offense:	Kit purge on the guilty character(s) and a week of jail.
2nd offense:	Deletion of guilty character(s).
3rd offense:	Deletion of all known multies and siteban.

For an immortal to pursue a reimb_lying judgment, however, the immortal 
must give the offender a chance to return the improper gear BEFORE pursuit.
This means that an imm may ask, "Are you sure that those pieces are all 
yours?" Or the imm may ask, "Are all those items the correct ones, no 
additions?" All they are required to do is verify the equipment with you.

SEE ALSO:  REIMBURSE_POLICY   

#
EQ_RECALLS EQUIP_RECALLING

Due to some issues with equipment errors (due in part to the occasional 
glitch or poor equipment checks), we are instituting a new "recall" policy.
Immortals have the right to confiscate items that are incorrect (an item 
missing minlevel flags, or items that are terribly unbalanced, etc.).  

This will NOT apply to "oldgen" equipment.  If the eq was INTENTIONALLY one
way and you legitimately earned the eq with stats that you were MEANT to 
have, immortals may not strip you of this gear.  If glitched eq or 
unbalanced eq is discovered, the eq will be confiscated AND REPLACED with 
the correct item.

This means you'll still have the item with the stats that the item was meant
to be popped or is allowed to be used.  For example, due to some weird 
glitch, you pop a serrated short sword that is 9d8 pierce.  This item is NOT
to be kept.  It follows the same basic policy of bugs.  We will trade you 
the correct serrated short sword. 

If the recalled item had extreme stats and the replacement is of obvious 
difference, the immortals MAY compensate you further with quest equipment, 
gold, a bless, etc.  The type of compensation, and whether you get one, is 
up to the imm.  You may NOT try to negotiate the compensation.

This policy goes into effect IMMEDIATELY.  If immortals approach you, please
comply.  We are striving to provide equal pieces (if not equal chances) for
the populace.

#
KILL_THEFT KILL_STEALING MOB_THEFT MOB_STEALING

Kill / Mob theft would be described as someone stealing the mob 
that you are currently fighting.  You must be fighting the mob 
or healing up and getting ready to go back to the mob for it to 
be considered theft.  You can not claim more than one mob at a 
time.  Hitting a mob and then running off to another zone due 
to your item popping, does not reserve that mob for you.

You may not monopolize mobs for yourself.  If you are not 
currently attempting to kill that mob, or healing yourself to 
do battle with that mob again, you may not claim it as solely
yours.

A good practice would be to see if the mobile is in excellent 
condition.  If it is not, find out who was attacking it, and if 
they are no longer fighting it.  Healing a mob to excellent 
condition does not give you the right to kill it.  If the mob's
status seems questionable to you, just ask if someone killing 
it currently.

- First offense for this act is a warning by an immortal and the
  compensation of coin and any eq popped from the stolen kill.
  This means you give the coins that you received from the mob 
  and any equipment gained from the mob to the player whom the 
  kill was stolen from.

- Second offense for this act is the same as the first offense, 
  plus two days in jail.

- Third offense will result in the purging of the thief's kit 
  and a week in jail.

- Subsequent offenses will be dealt with on a per case basis,
  by the immortal handling the issue.

See also:  POP_THEFT POP_THEFT2 POP_THEFT3

#
POP_THEFT

If a mob loads equipment, whoever killed it last gets the eq IF 
they stayed on to watch for the POP.  Logging on, killing a mob 
and then logging off does not give you rights to claim the eq 
if the mob pops.

Does this mean the mob belongs to you even if it doesn't pop? 
Of course not, this was covered in KILL_THEFT.  If the mob pops 
and someone else attacks it and promises to deliver the eq to 
the rightful owner, will that be okay?  Only if both parties 
consent to this course of action.

If someone pops a piece of eq and someone else gets the eq and 
returns it to the rightful owner, does the person who 'stole' 
the kill YET gave the eq away to the proper owner get the next 
pop?  Yep, they were the last person to kill the mob.

Remember the following however:
You may only claim ONE mob at a time.
You may only claim ONE pop at a time.
See the referenced help files for more details.

See also:  POP_THEFT2 POP_THEFT3 MOB_THEFT

#
POP_THEFT2

Pop theft has limited protection, and has aspects which are illegal.  Due to 
variable scenarios and possibilities, this file serves to outline the limits
of pop stealing (legal vs. illegal).

Following the tenets of mob stealing (a player may only claim one mob at a 
time, if they've attacked the mobs), the same holds true for pops.  If a 
player attacks a mob with the intent of popping a particular item, and that
item pops, they legally popped the item.  However, they may not run a series
of mobs and claim any and all items that pop UNLESS there are no other 
claims to that pop.  They can only claim one pop at a time.  If they are 
running a series of mobs and only one item pops, it's the original player's
pop.  If more than one item pops, you can only claim one.

Example:

Twinkie has been running the same four mobs for two hours.  No one else has
been killing those mobs, and two of the items on the mobs pop.  Twinkie is 
obviously faced with a decision on which pop he wants FIRST.  If he kills 
one mob and gets the pop, the pop is his.  The second pop, if no other 
claims are made, is also his if he kills the second mob.  However, if 
someone else claims the second pop while Twinkie is engaged on the first 
pop, Twinkie has no dominant claim to the item.  Of course, Twinkie does 
have the ability to inform and ask that the second pop go to him, but there
is nothing enforcing his right to the second pop.

SEE ALSO: POP_THEFT POP_THEFT3 MOB_THEFT

#
POP_THEFT3

If a player logs off, or logs off to log on a different player, the claim 
to any items previously is lost.  Only the original player involved in a 
popping run has any claim to a pop.

Example:

Twinkie decides for some reason to log off the Twinkie character and log on
a multi, Raisin.  After logging on as Raisin, he notices that one of the 
mobs he was running happened to pop and others are now running that mob.  
Due to logging off and in essence being a different player, Twinkie/Raisin 
has lost claim to that pop.

If a player is engaged in a run and is the rightful owner of a pop and pop 
theft occurs, the pop must be returned to the original player.  Due to the 
focus involved in claiming rights, those who violate legitimage popping 
claims face penalties ranging from jailing to kit purging IF the pop is not
returned to the rightful player.


SEE ALSO: POP_THEFT POP_THEFT2 MOB_THEFT  

#
ZONELORD

Zonelords are people who are creating new zones for the mud. They have
been granted special privileges in their respective area(s) to enable them
to do this. On the rest of the mud they are normal characters with regularly
earned mortal or immortal levels.

If you want to contribute toward CrimsonMud, the best and most common way is
to create a zone.  To create a zone you should have an active or committed
player for Crimson 2.  You do not necessarily need an avatar character.  The
zones are granted based on presentation and interest.  You need a reasonably
original idea, that fits in with the rest of the mud... Futuristic or 
modern-day zones are not accepted.

Once you have decided what you aim to do with a zone, mail the details to
Oldschool contact them via mudmail so that your proposal can be considered.

Before you will be given a blank zone to work with, you must have a clear 
idea of what you aim to achieve.  It is perfectly acceptable to alter things
as you go along, but you should not start from scratch with no idea of what 
you are going to do.

Also (except for special cases), your zone should fit within 100 rooms, 100
mobs it is rare for a zone to use more than about 30) and 100 objects 
(again it is rare for a zone to need even close to 100).

Once you have had an idea accepted, you will be given a blank zone on the
zoning port to work with, and instructions on how to use the online creation
facilities.

&RRestrictions:
The zonelord and his/her other multies are not to use equipment from the 
zone even if someone else goes to the zone to get it, during the first  
week the zone is live.  The zonelord is not allowed to tell others about
the zone.  Do not give guided tours or tell others (mortal or immortal)
about any items, mobs, rooms, etc.

Note, the zones designed here effectively become the property of the mud.  
We will of course give you copies of your files if you wish them, to do 
with as you please, however we reserve the right to keep the zone on this
mud, even if you should decide to leave.  You may ask to have your zones
removed, but under no circumstances do zoners have the right to remove zones 
unilaterally.  Crimson 2 bosses will make that decision.&n

#
PUFF

The cute, cuddly wuggly dragon that resides in Limbo. If you stay long 
enough, she may entertain you. ;)

#
BOTS

Bots are illegal here on Crimson 2. This has been changed for the benefit
of all players. We believe that botting is a disruption to characters who
are actively playing the game. It also goes against the spirit of the game.
Botting will not be tolerated on the game. First offense will result in 
jail time decided by the Imm staff one at the time. This will not exceed the
punishment for higher offenses, Second offense will be a week of jail, and
the  Third offense will result in being permanently banned from the game.

#
MOB_AUCTION "MOB AUCTIONS"

From time to time mobs will steal and auction an item from a
player it just killed.  Why?  To help recycle the equipment 
that is currently in play.  Any active player who is playing 
at the time may place a bid on these items.

Immortals have the right to interfere with these auctions as 
they see fit.  Some reasons for interference might include 
but are not limited to: auction caused by a loss to a quest 
mob, to deal with bids made by players who are not actively 
playing at the time [ie. bots, inactive visiting players, 
etc.], or to just be a good samaritan.  Immortals have the 
choice to interfere or not, but they should not at any time 
be expected to step in on anyone's behalf.
  
#
Harassment

Harassment is not taken lightly by Crimson II.  If someone is being
sexually harassing, it is an automatic day in jail for first offense,
a week for second and any subsequent offenses will be dealt with on a per
case basis.

Any other harassing actions will result in a warning from an Immortal.
If such actions do not cease, a day in jail will be given for first
offense.  Second offense will give you a week in jail and any subsequent
offenses will be dealt with on a per case basis.

Harassment is not limited to public channels, it could be actions or
done over private channels.  If you are caught, you will be punished.

#
