#
CRITICAL CHARGED "FLAME RUSH" "MISSILE MADNESS" CLASS_BONUS
This is a list of criticals that you get with your class at AVAT level.

Critical attack modifiers for classes:
*Note must have the move cost for criticals to have a chance of working

          Damage  Move cost
 Warrior  x 2        50
  Priest  x 1.25     10
    Bard  x 1.35     20
 Paladin  x 1.5      25
    Monk  x 2        50
Eldritch  x 1.35     25

Critical spell modifiers for classes:
*number(x,y) means a random number from x to y
*dice means it works just like dice so xdy

            Spell      Multiplier(Formula)
   Mage  firelance     	  x 2
         fireball      	  x 2
         firestorm     	  x 2
Eldritch firelance     	  x 1.5
         fireball      	  x 1.5
         firestorm     	  x 1.5

 Cleric  heal minor    	  x 2
         heal medium   	  x 2
         heal major   	  x 2
 Priest  cure critic   dice(number(3,18),number(8,48)) + number(WIS,INT*2)
   Bard  magic missile from 1-10 extra missiles
Paladin  heal minor   	  x 1.25
         heal medium   	  x 1.25
  Druid  thornwrack	  x 2
         needlestorm	  x 2
         sporecloud	  x 2
         wrath of nature  x 2

Critical backstab modifier for classes:

         Damage
  Thief  x 2

#
QM Sales
Randomly during a rush the Questmaster may decide to sell magical
forms.  This can be anything between monkey and dragon.  The
Questmaster being the all powerfull being that it might be can
cast a certain magical form upon you bringing up your abilities and
changing your damage.  The Questmaster however, is never cheap and
relies soley on quest points you earn from doing your quests.

Random chance of being able to buy forms is currently 25%

Example: quest transform 5 
This will transform you into the spirit of a bear.
See Also: help forms
 
#
DICE

This is a point of confusion for many.  Let's start with the basics.
First let's say you have a Serrated Short Sword at 2d8 damage.  
What does this mean exaclty?  Well this comes from the days of yore 
in  Dungeons and Dragons and other role playing games when it was 
all done with dice.   So what this means is it's the same as rolling 
2 dice with 8 sides each.  If you still don't understand think of a 
board game like Monopoly(tm).  In each turn you roll 2 dice to move.
The minimum you can roll is a 2, since there's  2 dice and the lowest 
number is 1.  The maximum is 12, since again you have 2 dice, with 6 
sides and the maximum of 6 on each die. So each turn you are moving 2d6! 
Get it?  Good! Ok.  Back to out 2d8 sword.  The minimum damage this sword 
will do is 2, since there's 2 dice.  The maximum is 16 since there's a 8 
sides on each die. Now as all of us Monopoly(tm) players know, neither 
one is very common. There are several dice average formula's out there, 
but a common one is like this: 
<# of dice> * <# sides>/2 + 3 
This looks complicated!  Not really.  
In our 2d8 example it would be 2 * 8 / 2 + 3 or, 16/2 + 3, or simply, 11.
So now you're thinking, ok, so the maximum is 16, the average is around 
11ish,  why am I hitting for 24 damage a round then?  Simple, you also 
have damage bonuses if you look in your attributes which come from 
attributes like strength and also from your equipment.  So if your Damage 
bonus is 15, you're swinging your short sword,  and your dice roll comes 
up 14, you add your 15 damage bonus and you just hit for 29!

If you still need help understanding, send detailed questions to 
c2admins@gmail.com

See Also: EQUIPMENT ATTRIBUTE
 
#~
~
